This paper focuses on the interaction between human cognitive constraints and network structure in affecting the diversity of information social media users receive. It uses a probabilistic model to measure the diversity of information users receive from their social media contacts. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also touches on topics related to social media, information retrieval, and natural language processing, which are covered by sub-categories cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks), cs.IR (Information Retrieval), cs.CL (Computation and Language), and cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy).
